A '''"Predictable Surprise"''' describes a situation or circumstance in which avoidable crises are marginalized in order to satisfy economic and social policies.
==Definition== [[Max H. Bazerman]] and [[Michael D. Watkins]] define "predictable surprises" as problems that * at least some people are aware of, * are getting worse over time, and * are likely to explode into a crisis eventually, * but are not prioritized by key decision-makers or have not elicited a response fast enough to prevent severe damage.
The problems behind "predictable surprises" tend to require a significant investment in the near term that will not pay off until later. This could involve changes to established organization culture and/or changes that competing interests do not benefit from.
== Examples of predictable surprises ==
* [[Iraq War]] * [[Enron scandal]] * [[Subprime mortgage crisis]]<ref>Watkins, M (2007)[http://www.businessweek.com/managing/content/dec2007/ca20071213_764745.htm BusinessWeek (December 17) Subprime: A Predictable Surprise]</ref> * [[Criticism of government response to Hurricane Katrina|Hurricane Katrina Response]]<ref>Irons, L (2005) [http://www.hsaj.org/pages/volume1/issue2/pdfs/1.2.7.pdf Homeland Security Affairs Hurricane Katrina as A Predictable Surprise]{{dead link|date=March 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> * [[Global Warming]]<ref>Bazerman, M (2006) Climate change as a predictable surprise.''Climatic Change'' 77:79-193</ref> * [[Roman Catholic sex abuse cases]]
