The '''Pritzker family''' is an [[United States|American]] family engaged in [[entrepreneurship]] and [[philanthropy]], and [[List of wealthiest families|one of the wealthiest families]] in the United States of America, being near the top of ''[[Forbes]]'' magazine's "America's Richest Families" list since the magazine began listings in 1982.
The family owns the [[Hyatt]] hotel chain, and the [[Marmon Group]], a conglomerate of manufacturing and industrial service companies that has since been sold to [[Berkshire Hathaway]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Bajaj|first1=Vikas|title=Rapidly, Buffett Secures a Deal for $4.5 Billion|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2007/12/26/business/26deal.html|accessdate=29 October 2015|newspaper=The New York Times|date=December 26, 2007}}</ref> Other holdings have included the [[Superior Bank of Chicago]], which collapsed in 2001, the [[TransUnion]] [[credit bureau]], [[Braniff (1983–1990)|Braniff]] airlines, ''[[McCall's]]'' magazine, and the [[Royal Caribbean International|Royal Caribbean]] [[cruise line]]. The company of the family Pritzker Group was the second largest contributor to the Clinton Campaign in 2016.<ref>https://www.opensecrets.org/pres16/contributors?id=N00000019</ref>
The Pritzker family is of [[Jewish]] descent<ref name=the-family>{{cite web|title=Pritzker family|url=http://www.britannica.com/EBchecked/topic/477277/Pritzker-family|work=[[Encyclopædia Britannica]]|accessdate=20 September 2013}}</ref> and based in [[Chicago]], [[Illinois]].<ref name=":0">{{Cite news|url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/2005-06-12/news/0506120282_1_penny-pritzker-jay-pritzker-family-businesses|title=Inside the Pritzker family feud|newspaper=Chicago Tribune|access-date=2016-03-21}}</ref>
==Family business== In 1995, Jay Pritzker, the cofounder of Hyatt, stepped down and Thomas Pritzker took control of [[The Pritzker Organization]].<ref name=":0" /> When Jay died in 1999, the family split the business into 11 pieces worth $1.4 billion each,<ref name=":0" /> but had to settle a lawsuit from two family members who apparently received $500 million each in 2005.<ref name="NEWYORKTIMESwilgoren">[https://www.nytimes.com/2005/01/07/us/900-million-accord-enables-breakup-of-pritzker-dynasty.html "$900 Million Accord Enables Breakup of Pritzker Dynasty"], Jodi Wilgoren, ''[[The New York Times]]'', January 7, 2005</ref><ref>[http://articles.chicagotribune.com/2004-02-12/business/0402120309_1_liesel-pritzker-robert-pritzker-matthew-pritzker ''Chicago Tribune'']. "Judge sets hearing on sealed Pritzker cases" by Susan Chandler (February 12, 2004)</ref><ref name=VF>{{cite web|publisher=Vanity Fair |title=Shattered Dynasty |date=2007-06-01 |url=http://www.vanityfair.com/magazine/2007/06/postscript200706 |accessdate=2011-11-05}}</ref> In 2011, the dissolution had been completed and the cousins had gone their separate ways, with some pursuing business and others pursuing philanthropic or artistic ventures.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/2011-12-18/business/ct-biz-1218-pritzkers-mainbar--20111218_1_hyatt-center-pritzker-military-library-wealth|title=Pritzker family agreement to divide wealth comes to a close|newspaper=Chicago Tribune |access-date=2016-03-21}}</ref>
