{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2014}}
{{Use New Zealand English|date=October 2014}}
'''Trevor Davey''' (5 July 1926 – 13 February 2012) was a [[Member of Parliament]] from [[Gisborne, New Zealand|Gisborne]] in the [[North Island]] of New Zealand who represented the [[New Zealand Labour Party|Labour Party]].

==Biography==
{{NZ parlbox header|nolist=true|align=right}}
{{NZ parlbox
 |start      = {{NZ election link year|1972}}
 |end        = 1975
 |term       = 37th
 |electorate = {{NZ electorate link|Gisborne}}
 |party      = New Zealand Labour Party
}}
{{NZ parlbox footer}}
Davey was born in [[Didsbury]], Lancashire, England in 1926, the son of H. W. Davey. He received his education at [[Chorlton High School]].<ref name="Who's Who">{{cite book | page=95 | title=[[Who's Who in New Zealand]] | edition=11th | editor-first=James Edward | editor-last=Traue | date=1978 | publisher=Reed | location=Wellington}}</ref> Davey was a member of the [[6th Airborne Division (United Kingdom)|6th Airborne Division]] from 1946 to 1948.<ref name="Who's Who" /> He married Mavis Birch Baxter in [[Manchester]] in 1949, the daughter of H. A. Baxter. They had one son.<ref name="Who's Who" />

He was the managing director of Queen's Hall, [[Leeds]] between 1956 and 1966.<ref name="Who's Who" /> Davey emigrated to New Zealand with his wife and son in 1966.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://familysearch.org/pal:/MM9.3.1/TH-266-12589-47408-37?cc=1609792 |title=New Zealand, Archives New Zealand, passenger lists, 1839–1973 |date= |website= |publisher=FamilySearch |accessdate=18 April 2015}}</ref>

Davey served on the Gisborne City Council from 1971 to 1974.<ref name="Who's Who" /> He represented the [[Gisborne (New Zealand electorate)|Gisborne]] electorate in the [[New Zealand House of Representatives]] from {{NZ election link year|1972}}, when he beat the incumbent, [[Esme Tombleson]], the first woman who had represented Gisborne in Parliament.<ref name=Wilson /><ref>{{cite news|last1=Falconer|first1=Phoebe|title=From stage to politics on her own terms|url=http://www.nzherald.co.nz/nz/news/article.cfm?c_id=1&objectid=10664320|accessdate=28 August 2015|work=[[The New Zealand Herald]]|date=7 August 2010}}</ref> At the next election in {{NZ election link year|1975}}, he was defeated by [[New Zealand National Party|National]]'s [[Bob Bell (politician)|Bob Bell]].<ref name="Wilson">{{cite book |last= Wilson |first= James Oakley |title= New Zealand parliamentary record, 1840–1984 |edition= 4 |origyear= First ed. published 1913 |year= 1985 |publisher= V.R. Ward, Govt. Printer |location= Wellington |isbn= |oclc= 154283103 |page= |pages=183, 192}}</ref> He was awarded the [[New Zealand 1990 Commemoration Medal]] for service to the community.{{Citation needed|date=October 2012}}

Davey was a governor of both [[Gisborne Boys' High School|Gisborne Boys']] and [[Gisborne Girls' High School]]s. He was on the executive of the [[New Zealand Red Cross]] (1972–1973).<ref name="Who's Who" />

